The ten vaccines employ three different technologies. In the first-generation vaccines, the virus is either weakened
(attenuated) by growing it in another species, or inactivated by heat or chemicals. There are two first-generation producers: (1) Sinovac (called Coronavac) and (2) Sinopharm. The second-generation vaccines take advantage of molecular biology advances to include specific viral proteins or protein fragments in the vaccine instead of a whole
virus. There are five second-generation vaccine producers: (3) Novavax, (4) Oxford/AstraZeneca vaccine (called
Covidshield when produced in India), (5) Gamaleya Research Institute (called Sputnik V), (6) Janssen (J&J), and (7) CanSino. The third-generation vaccines aim to vaccinate a patient with genetic materialâ€”RNAâ€”that encodes for the desired viral protein target. In the case of SARS-CoV-2, the target that researchers have decided is the most promising is the spike protein, a protein on the surface of the virus that enables it to invade host cells. There are three third-generation vaccine producers: (8) Pfizer-BioNTech, (9) Moderna, and (10) Bharat Biotech (called Covaxin).

Broadly there are 2 types of virus

1) RNA Virus (Gnome based on : Ribonucleic Acid)
2) DNA Virus (Gnome based on : Deoxyribonucleic acid)

COVID-19 Coronavirus is RNA based Virus. All those viruses which has RNA as their Gnome and DNA intermediates in their replication process are known as Retrovirus. For example, HIV is a famous Retrovirus. Comon Cold Flu is an other daily life example of Retrovirus. All those viruses which comes under RNA Gnome has exponentially high mutation rate as compared to a DNA based virus.

Just because you have the COVID-19 vaccine doesn't mean you are protected against COVID-19 because there are mutated variants for Example by now we have seen Chinese variant, Indian variant, UK variant, Brazilian variant etc. There are more variants to follow up in coming days. As I often say, sooner or later everyone will be infected with COVID-19 irrespective of your measures taken against it. It's simply an inevitable process. Vaccine is not protecting us against COVID-19, it's only controlling the effects generated by the COVID-19 after our body is infected with the virus.

If you want to explore more then I would recommend you to have a look at some articles and research papers based RNA viruses.

The "reassuring" conclusions in this report regarding modest transmissibility increases of the Indian variants over the wild virus relative to other VOCs is in stark contrast to what is being seen on the ground.  Due to its high transmissibility, the U.K. variant (B.117) has out-competed every other variant, very quickly becoming the dominant variant almost everywhere it has been introduced.  In essence, it has become the new pandemic because of this competitive advantage in transmissibility.   But now in the U.K., where B.117 had quickly become dominant within months of it's discovery, it is being dramatically out-competed by the Indian variant (specifically B.1.617.2) and wherever there are clusters of increased covid incidence, genomic testing shows rapidly increasing proportions of B.1.617.2.   Its seems to spread like wildfire, even over B.117.and it now appears almost inevitable that the B.1617.2 will very quickly become the dominant variant in the U.K.  Why the conclusions of this report should not reflect that is a mystery to me.   Perhaps, of the several distinct variants of the B.1.617 lineage, the B.1.617.2, which has shown itself to be far and away the most transmissible,  was not the focus or even included in this report.  But whatever the cause of this apparent contradiction, the reassuring message of modest or intermediate transmissibility of the "B.1.617" may be tragically misleading.

A letter I'm sending to my GP.  Please feel free to share and use if you wish. 

5th March 2021

Dear Dr.  

I am writing to you regarding the COVID-19 vaccination programme which your surgery has contacted me about.

Thank you very much for your concern and care.  As an intelligent and discerning individual, I am able to access the scientific literature, via PubMed and other reputable sources, and have done my own studies of the various SARS-CoV-2 vaccines in order to make an independent and properly informed decision.

Having reviewed the available evidence in depth, I have made the informed choice not to accept your offer of a SARS-CoV-2 vaccination.  While I know it is my right to decline any medical treatment offered to me without explanation, I will happily outline my reasons here in writing for the record.

In the first instance, this vaccine has already been reported on many occasions around the world to have caused actual bodily harm and even death in a small overall percentage of recipients, something which must not sit well with those promoting it after having taken the Hippocratic oath.  These risks of harm are confirmed on the UK Government's website, where they state that a structured compensation programme has been organised for those left severely damaged by COVID-19 vaccinations.  

Secondly, the actual evidence of a need for the inoculation of the entire general population against SARS-CoV-2 appears to be very weak.  Studies of this virus, and its predecessor SARS-CoV-1, strongly suggest that people who have recovered from a natural coronavirus infection have a more robust and resilient natural immune protection against the disease than those who take the vaccine.   This, in combination with the knowledge that SARS-CoV-2 infection is mild for most healthy people, does not usually require hospital treatment, and the overwhelming majority of people go on to make a full recovery with no lasting negative effects, naturally leads one to question why you are promoting a vaccine to people without knowing if they have already had exposure to the virus and developed natural immunity? 

Finally, eminent authorities in vaccine science, have issued earnest warnings about the dangers of vaccine development for coronaviruses in particular.  Attempts to develop coronavirus vaccines in the past, have resulted in test subjects developing a well documented condition called Antibody Dependent Enhancement (ADE), also known as pathogenic priming, whereby, when a recipient comes into contact with the wild virus against which they have been inoculated, they are at significant risk of developing a more severe illness than those who did not receive an inoculation.  This occurs due to the paradoxical development of disease enhancing binding-antibodies, rather than disease-mitigating neutralizing-antibodies.  Iâ€™m curious to know why you are not properly informing the public of the risks of ADE/pathogenic priming, a concern which was published in the medical literature during the trials - "Informed consent disclosure to vaccine trial subjects of risk of COVID-19 vaccines worsening clinical disease" - https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33113270/  
 
In conclusion, I reiterate that I do not wish to receive a SARS-CoV-2/COVID-19 vaccination for the above reasons, nor do I wish to be the recipient of any further promotional communication from you about this.  However, I would be interested to hear your response to the above questions.  I shall add references to the base of this correspondence for your attention.

Thank you very much.
 
Yours sincerely,
 
 

 
References â€“

"Vaccine-induced enhancement of viral infections" - https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7131326/

One very important point about the South African variant, is that the primary selection pressure will not be to make it more infectious by being a better fit with the Ace 2 receptor, but the evasion of acquired immunity, either through natural infection, or by vaccination. We would expect to see such mutations where there is a high incidence of previous exposure, and this, indeed, appears to be what happened in South Africa. 

The good news is that its unlikely to suddenly stop all acquired immunity to disappear, but it will gradually degrade it. We are going to be playing a game of virus variant Whack-a-Mole for years, and that is possibly an answer to those that question why the UK has ordered, or has options for enough vaccine doses to give everybody in the UK 6 jabs as, presumably the later batches can be tweaked to encompass more variants.

I should add that I'm particularly impressed by the Novavax vaccine as it seems to me it's much faster to change and get new formulations into the delivery chain at the same time as being robust. The mRNA vaccines are, at the moment at least, a bit too fragile for easy deployment and it's especially a problem in poorer countries. However, they can be altered very fast with new formulations being delivered into production in weeks (approval depending).

Whilst the Oxford vaccine can also be tweaked in days, there remains a concern about acquired immunity to the viral vector. The Jenner Institute specifically chose a chimp, rather than human adenovirus for the vector as it was unlikely their would be any significant resistance to it in the human population. However, it might be that, if humans are subject to repeated doses of the vector, then immunity to that will make it a lot less effective over time. I suppose a new vector may be used, but that could well mean spending much more time on clinical trials for safety. In contrast, the mRNA and encapsulated protein approaches would seem much less likely to be vulnerable.

In Brazil, the E484K mutation (glutamic acid to lysine substitution at amino acid 484) also arose independently and was identified in Rio de Janeiro state (Southeast Brazil) in early-October in P.2 lineage (Voloch et al., 2020)."

The UK does 45% of the worlds genomic sequencing, but the highest rate of sequencing by population is Denmark, which sequences every single infection - an outstanding achievement, and probably responsible for the very low spread of the variant they had, which they managed to confine to a small region within Denmark, which is already a small country. 
So these are the two countries most likely to pick up new variants, even if they didn't start there.  Germany also does fairly well by the number of sequences performed, but no so much as a proportion of cases.  Australia, Taiwan and New Zealand manage to sequence all cases, but that is because they have so few (well done to them for acting so rapidly to stamp it out and close borders!).
Other countries vary in both capacity and speed of sequencing, and it is fair to say that just about anywhere else in the world, a new strain is probably well established by the time it is picked up in sequencing, simply because the overwhelming majority of cases are never sequenced. 
For its population, scientific capability and wealth, the USA's level of sequencing is a bad joke, sadly.  But when you have people refusing to be tested "in case they have their constitutional freedoms restricted", it is unsurprising that new strains are probably endemic by the time they are found.  The US has a quarter of the world's recorded cases, but not one identified new variant at all, which probably means they just don't find them until they get notified by another country and go looking.

The order of importance in dealing with COIVD is stopping deaths, hospitalizations and then infections. So far, every vaccine with phase 3 trial results has stopped both hospitalizations and deaths, regardless of how effective they are in stopping symptomatic infections. No vaccinated person in a phase 3 trial for the Pfizer, Moderna, or Astro-Zeneca vaccine has ended up in hospital or has died from COVID.

In the province of Ontario, Canada with about 15 million people 70% of covid deaths over the last year are for those over 80, and 25% for those between 60 and 80. The percentage of the population over 80 is about 5%, and between 60 and 80 about 20%. These death statistics and population distribution are likely very similar in most developed countries. Therefore, when every older person is vaccinated then once the vaccines take effect hospitalizations and deaths from COVID should decline by around 90 to 95%. That should stop the overloading of the medical system, and in fact it is critical that this actually happens.

Since millions are now being vaccinated it is easy to verify that for the vast majority the vaccines stop hospitalization and deaths simply by checking if a new COVID patient has already been vaccinated. In Israel about 60% of people over 60 are already vaccinated with the Pfizer vaccine. Therefore, in three to six weeks there should be a big drop in hospitalizations and deaths in this country (there is of course a delay between being infected and going to hospital). Other countries should follow soon after as more people become vaccinated. 

Achieving herd immunity only decreases the likelihood of COVID spreading, it does not change the outcome for someone who is infected. In the US Scott Gottlieb, former FDA commissioner, estimates that around 60 million people who over 60 will take the vaccine, but after that there are many people in the US who will not. So, herd immunity may take a long time to achieve, but it does not really matter. The US manufactures both the Pfizer and Moderna vaccine locally, and in a few months more vaccine manufacturers will almost certainly come online. So, once older people are vaccinated the overloading of the health system will stop and this will happen long before the US achieves herd immunity. 

Finally, the US is fortunate that the vaccine manufacturing takes place inside the country. This means that they will be able to offer vaccine to their entire population between two and four months before other developed countries like Canada, that must import all their vaccine. 

To conclude, I think my chain of reasoning is both evidence based and sound. Does anyone disagree?

Discussions like these highlight the need for *universal* treatment/prevention (i.e. no vaccine or monoclonal antibodies)  that is also not harmful (and preferably has *positive* side-effects). Here are some of them:
* Block airborne transmission through adequate ventilation (CO2 < 1000 ppm) and optimal humidity (RH between 40% and 60%; https://40to60rh.com/)
* Optimize immune system through vitamin D (>40 ng/ml), zinc, healthy lifestyle and diet. Japan has a very old population and high population density, but no excess all cause mortality (the least bad data on C19 mortality), partly because their elderly have a healthy lifestyle with adequate vitamin D and eat real food instead of (ultra)processed junk.
* Ivermectin, quercetin
* High or mega doses of vitamin C. Dr. Robert Cathcart mentions the case of a 45 kg woman with severe mononucleosis who took 450 grams (!!!!!) of oral vitamin C within 48 hours "without so much as gas". https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=j6G-5n0IG8E
* Intranasal iodine, spread via Q-tip, nasal spray or nasal rinse. Also mouth rinse and gargling (Listerine and antiseptic rinses work). See for instance dr. Ricardo Persaud https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VNFJ_IPwZ-g. See also dr. Cameron Jones: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BYuwtcsqNCo
* Nebulized 0.1% hydrogen peroxide and/or iodine. https://www.bitchute.com/video/QoRi6bu3sMEV/ I first had my doubts whether this is safe. This article and many experiences of people who have used this for years/decades have convinced me that this is safe enough and at least less dangerous than a severe infection. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7308628/. I know that dr. Paul Marik is dismissive of nebulized 3% hydrogen peroxide, but 3% is 30x larger than the dose I mentioned. We should not categorically dismiss anything until there is proof of danger or inefficacy.
* Intravenous medical ozone https://clinmedjournals.org/articles/jide/journal-of-infectious-diseases-and-epidemiology-jide-6-113.php and https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G_cvrcx_7m8
* Inhaled steroids, e.g. budesonide
* Hyperthermia therapy. Fever is a functional reaction of the body against infections. If you take antipyretics, you hamper the body's immune response. Aspirin may have a place due to anticlotting and antiviral properties, but then should be combined with treatment to get core body temperature up. Examples: regular hot showers or sauna, physical activity in sweat clothes, crawling into bed with many blankets and thick clothes. I think the only real selection pressure is in long haulers and convalescent plasma patients. That's why we suddenly see variants that have a dozen scary mutations, we don't see intermediates, and can never trace the lineage. It's because each of these variants was created inside a single patient.

If this is true, then we don't have to be concerned about, for example, the UK and SA variants somehow combining.  I read about viral recombination - it's never been observed with this virus, and leaves telltale "loops" in the sequences.  I didn't understand exactly what the loops were, but was convinced from reading several papers that if viral recombination were occurring, we could determine that. So the lineages will keep diverging.

Some of the mutations are appearing spontaneously in several parts of the world, notably N501Y, E484K, P681H, and K417N.  In my opinion, all of them are escape mutations because there are no other selection pressures, other than antibodies in long haulers.  The virus spreads before a person's immune system has really become active, or seroconverted, so it has spread before there is selection pressure from antibodies. Not so in long haulers, and especially, in a person undergoing plasma therapy.

One theory of why the b117 variant is more transmissible is that the N501Y mutation increases the binding affinity to the angiotensin 2 receptor, making it "stickier" or bind better, or be attracted more, so it is more infectious.  Some have argued this effect outside of the body - it sticks in your nasal passages better.  But according to my long hauler theory, the binding affinity is not the most important thing, antibodies are.  The measureable increase in viral loads (among b117 patients) means people are shedding more virus, and this would make the virus more transmissible.  People have higher viral loads because the virus has evolved to escape the main antibodies produced, and is already a step ahead.  Those higher viral loads they measured in the UK are really bad news, by the way. 

The last theory I will write on your youtube comment (thanks!) is that the Chinese vaccine Sinovac has performed poorly in Brazil because the E484K mutation is already prevalent there. This is a warning of what we can expect, as the SA and Brazilian variants come into the US. Plan on reinfections, and vaccine effectiveness dropping significantly.

Status of COVID-19
As of 19 March 2020, COVID-19 is no longer considered to be a high consequence infectious disease (HCID) in the UK.

The 4 nations public health HCID group made an interim recommendation in January 2020 to classify COVID-19 as an HCID. This was based on consideration of the UK HCID criteria about the virus and the disease with information available during the early stages of the outbreak. Now that more is known about COVID-19, the public health bodies in the UK have reviewed the most up to date information about COVID-19 against the UK HCID criteria. They have determined that several features have now changed; in particular, more information is available about mortality rates (low overall), and there is now greater clinical awareness and a specific and sensitive laboratory test, the availability of which continues to increase.

The Advisory Committee on Dangerous Pathogens (ACDP) is also of the opinion that COVID-19 should no longer be classified as an HCID.

The need to have a national, coordinated response remains, but this is being met by the governmentâ€™s COVID-19 response.

Cases of COVID-19 are no longer managed by HCID treatment centres only. All healthcare workers managing possible and confirmed cases should follow the updated national infection and prevention (IPC) guidance for COVID-19, which supersedes all previous IPC guidance for COVID-19. This guidance includes instructions about different personal protective equipment (PPE) ensembles that are appropriate for different clinical scenarios.
